					<h4>Western Book Roundup</h4>
		
		<h1>Peter Hessler&#8217;s Take on Life in Southern Colorado</h1>
		<h2><i></i></h2>
		<div class="text-feature_print">
							<p>By Jenny Shank, 4-21-10</p>
			
			
							<p>After reporting on the AWP Conference for a couple of weeks, I have accumulated a lot of odds and ends for this week&#8217;s Roundup.&nbsp; Shall we dive in?
</p>
<p>
&#8226; Peter Hessler, the China correspondent for The New Yorker, has a delightful account of his one-year move to rural Colorado in the April 19 issue.&nbsp; After living in China since 1996, Hessler and his wife Leslie decided to move home to the United States for a year to work on book projects.&nbsp; They chose, almost at random, to make their new home in Colorado.&nbsp; Hessler writes in <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2010/04/19/100419fa_fact_hessler" title=""Go West: Scenes from an American Homecoming"">&#8220;Go West: Scenes from an American Homecoming&#8221;</a>:
</p>
<p>
&#8220;I liked the big bright landscapes, the way the mountains caught the alpenglow in late afternoon, and I liked the heavy-named towns that sat in the valleys: Granite, Bedrock, Sawpit, Crested Butte.&nbsp; In southwestern Colorado, we followed the Uncompahgre River for miles; just seeing that name on a sign made me happy.&#8221;
</p>
<p>
Hessler and his wife rent a house in Ridgway for one year, and throw themselves into the life of the town, attending rodeos and high school football games.&nbsp; (If you haven&#8217;t read Hessler&#8217;s <I>River Town</I> or other books, you are missing out.&nbsp; Reading Hessler&#8217;s inquisitive and insightful writing helped me understand a lot more of what I was witnessing when I traveled to China several years ago.)
</p>
<p>
&#8226; <a target="_blank" href="http://www.deannestillman.com" title="Deanne Stillman">Deanne Stillman</a> reports that her book <I><a target="_blank" href="http://www.deannestillman.com/mustang.shtml" title="Mustang: The Saga of the Wild Horse in the American West">Mustang: The Saga of the Wild Horse in the American West</a></I>, which <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/comanche_the_horse_that_survived_the_battle_of_the_little_bighorn_part_1/C39/L39/" title="we excerpted on New West">we excerpted on New West</a> a few years ago, is under option for two different film projects.&nbsp; The first: actress <a target="_blank" href="http://www.nypost.com/p/pagesix/mustang_maven_hq06EqXvQChbcPRHZj8JWL" title="Wendie Malick optioned the "Wild Horse Annie" material in the book for a film">Wendie Malick optioned the &#8220;Wild Horse Annie&#8221; material in the book for a film</a> that she&#8217;ll star in.&nbsp; Stillman and Malick are developing it with producer Helen Bartless ("North Country") and screenwriter Jenny Wingfield ("Man in the Moon").&nbsp; The second: the Denver-based, Academy Award-nominated documentary filmmaker Henry Ansbacher is working on a film based on the entire book.
</p>
<p>
If anyone in southern California is reading this, Stillman will be at the <a target="_blank" href="http://events.latimes.com/festivalofbooks/" title="Los Angeles Times Festival of Books">Los Angeles Times Festival of Books</a> on April 25, appearing on a panel with Charles Bowden, Nick Schou, and Miles Corwin entitled <a target="_blank" href="http://events.latimes.com/festivalofbooks/program-schedule/sunday-panels/" title=""Life on the Edge: Violence and the West."">&#8220;Life on the Edge: Violence and the West.&#8221;</a> 
</p>
<p>
&#8226; Denver&#8217;s Lighthouse Writers Workshop is expanding to Boulder for the first time this month, with <a target="_blank" href="https://lighthousewriters.org/workshop/detail/id/304/" title=""Writing 101: Gotta Start Somewhere"">&#8220;Writing 101: Gotta Start Somewhere&#8221;</a> taught by <a target="_blank" href="http://www.writelifecoaching.com/novelsdoug.htm" title="Doug Kurtz">Doug Kurtz</a>, author of the novel <I>Mosquito</I>, which <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/an_interview_with_douglas_kurtz/C39/L39/" title="we discussed on New West">we discussed on New West</a>.&nbsp; The first class was yesterday at Vic&#8217;s in South Boulder, so I&#8217;m a little late with this, but I understand there will be future Boulder offerings from Lighthouse. 
</p>
<p>
&#8226; Denver novelist <a target="_blank" href="http://www.nickarvin.com/" title="Nick Arvin">Nick Arvin</a> recently had a new story <a target="_blank" href="http://www.fiftytwostories.com/?p=1153#more-1153" title=""An Outbreak of Armed Hostilities,"">&#8220;An Outbreak of Armed Hostilities,&#8221;</a> featured in FiftyTwoStories.com.&nbsp; Arvin&#8217;s second novel, <i>The Reconstructionist</i>, will be published by Harper Perennial next year.
</p>
<p>
&#8226; I recently reviewed Louisville, Colo.-based author Adriana Lisboa&#8217;s elegant novel, &#8220;Symphony in White,&#8221; for <a target="_blank" href="http://www.dailycamera.com/books/ci_14847409" title="the Boulder Daily Camera">the Boulder Daily Camera</a>.&nbsp; Lisboa grew up in Brazil.&nbsp; Her novel won the Jos&#233; Saramago Prize in 2003, and it has just been released in an English edition, translated from the Portuguese by Sarah Green.
</p>
<p>
&#8226; Margie Wilson and Frank Cooley, owners of Twice Upon A Time Bookshop in Grand Junction, Colo., will open their second bookstore in early May.&nbsp; Grand Valley Books will be located at 350 Main Street in downtown Grand Junction.&nbsp; Wilson noted in a press release, &#8220;With a  mix of new and used  books, [we] plan to focus on regional history and  Western  Americana titles as well as Native Americana topics.&#8221;  Sharon Sullivan of Grand Junction Free Press <a target="_blank" href="http://www.gjfreepress.com/article/20090206/COMMUNITY_NEWS/902059963" title="profiled the bookstore last year">profiled the bookstore last year</a>.
</p>
<p>
&#8226; <a target="_blank" href="http://www.kauiharthemmings.com" title="Kaui Hart Hemmings">Kaui Hart Hemmings</a>, author of the novel <I>The Descendents</I>, reported via <a target="_blank" href="http://twitter.com/kauihemmings" title="Twitter">Twitter</a> that she&#8217;s setting her next novel in Vail.&nbsp; &#8220;I guess I need to go to Vail then?&#8221; she asks.&nbsp; Hemmings grew up in Hawaii and lives there currently, but she does have some Colorado cred: she earned her undergraduate degree from Colorado College.
</p>
<p>
Please follow me on <a target="_blank" href="http://www.twitter.com/jennyshank" title="Twitter">Twitter</a> and <script type="text/javascript">
